      Tesla perks
   =20
 =20

I=C2=A0think that if you are a Tesla Inc. investor the deal you are signing=
 up for is:
=09Elon Musk is a bad and annoying chief executive officer by almost every =
conventional metric.
  [1]
 He is distracted by running  several  other  companies and by weird person=
al projects and by getting in  dumb fights online. He constantly gets in  t=
rouble with  regulators and says things about Tesla=C2=A0that   aren=E2=80=
=99t true. He is  rude and unhelpful to analysts on earnings calls.=C2=A0He=
 overpromises and  underdelivers. He loves   doing transactions that create=
   conflicts of interest, that make no business sense=C2=A0and that seem to=
 advance his interests over those of shareholders. The board of directors i=
s stocked with his loyalists and brother. His pay package is comically,   p=
erhaps illegally large.=C2=A0His impulsiveness makes Tesla=E2=80=99s stock =
more volatile: He sometimes pumps up the price=C2=A0by   making false publi=
c statements, and sometimes knocks it down by   tweeting that it should go =
down.=C2=A0=09Tesla makes cool electric cars and sells them for, increasing=
ly, a profit, and over time the stock goes up a lot. It=E2=80=99s up more t=
han=C2=A0100% year-to-date, though it had a rough 2022, and up more than 1,=
000% over the last five years.=C2=A0Tesla=E2=80=99s equity market capitaliz=
ation is about $850 billion, value that Musk has, in a fairly direct sense,=
 created for shareholders.

My assumption is that every Tesla shareholder
  [2]
=C2=A0is=C2=A0very happy=C2=A0with this tradeoff. They are in the stock mos=
tly to make money, and whatever Musk=E2=80=99s other problems are, he=C2=A0=
does make them money. Also some of them are in the stock a little bit to be=
 entertained by Musk=E2=80=99s antics, and while not everyone finds=C2=A0th=
ose antics=C2=A0entertaining, presumably the shareholders do.=C2=A0
This is, I think, very true of Tesla=E2=80=99s meme-stock-y retail investor=
s, but it is also pretty clearly true of a more institutional class of Elon=
 Musk fans. When Musk went off on his apparently harebrained and so-far-mon=
ey-losing acquisition of Twitter Inc., several big investment firms and bil=
lionaires clamored to join him, happily writing big checks with no due dili=
gence. The thinking   seems to have been=C2=A0=E2=80=9Cthis guy does a lot =
of nonsense but he has made us a lot of money, so let=E2=80=99s see where t=
his goes,=E2=80=9D which strikes me as a perfectly rational investment thes=
is.
In fact the whole deal strikes me as perfectly rational, and quite good, fo=
r Tesla=E2=80=99s shareholders.=C2=A0I personally am not a huge fan of Musk=
=E2=80=99s antics, but then, I don=E2=80=99t own Tesla stock.
  [3]
=C2=A0If you offered to let me travel back in time to 2018 and take this de=
al =E2=80=94=C2=A0=E2=80=9Cyou put your money in Tesla stock, Elon Musk wil=
l make it go up 10x, but he=E2=80=99ll do a lot of nonsense along the way=
=E2=80=9D =E2=80=94=C2=A0I would absolutely take it. I=E2=80=99d tune out t=
he nonsense and enjoy=C2=A0the money. Or I=E2=80=99d even enjoy the nonsens=
e. =E2=80=9COh you scamp, using Tesla to bail out another company you own, =
good thing you=E2=80=99re making me all this money,=E2=80=9D I=E2=80=99d ch=
uckle, like many Tesla shareholders do.
If you are an investor in Space Exploration Technologies Corp. =E2=80=94=C2=
=A0SpaceX, Musk=E2=80=99s second-biggest company =E2=80=94=C2=A0you get bas=
ically the same deal.   Conflicted transactions, conflicted board of direct=
ors, constant distractions, occasional rocket explosions, but also he built=
 a successful space company from scratch and it=E2=80=99s   worth like $150=
 billion.=C2=A0
But SpaceX is a private company,
  [4]
=C2=A0and Tesla is a public company. With a private company, the deal betwe=
en the entrepreneur and the investors can kind of be whatever you want: The=
 company can have more or less whatever contractual terms or informal under=
standings or governance structure the entrepreneur and the investors agree =
to. If Musk comes to the board of SpaceX and says =E2=80=9Chey you need to =
lend me $1 billion for a week so I can win this fight I=E2=80=99m having on=
line,=E2=80=9D the board can be like =E2=80=9Csure here you go you little r=
ascal.=E2=80=9D It might not even have to tell shareholders. And if the sha=
reholders find out in the newspaper they can be like =E2=80=9Clol that=E2=
=80=99s our boy=E2=80=9D and everyone can be perfectly happy about it.=C2=
=A0
Whereas with a public company, there are just rules that apply to all publi=
c companies, and that constrain the deals you can make. There are standard =
rules, enshrined in the US securities laws, regulating what companies have =
to disclose to investors and how they have to communicate and what their re=
lationship with their CEO can look like. And if you break those rules it is=
 mostly not a defense to say, like, =E2=80=9Cbut my shareholders love me an=
d think this is funny,=E2=80=9D or =E2=80=9Cbut look how much money I am ma=
king for them.=E2=80=9D
If Elon Musk says nonsense about SpaceX online and his investors are happy,=
 then it=E2=80=99s fine.
  [5]
=C2=A0If Elon Musk says nonsense about Tesla online and his investors are h=
appy, but the US Securities and Exchange Commission is not happy, then  the=
 SEC can step in and fine him $20 million and make him stop being Tesla=E2=
=80=99s board chairman. Is that what Tesla=E2=80=99s shareholders wanted? P=
robably not, no, but a public company is not just a deal between Musk and h=
is shareholders; the SEC gets a say too.
