A basic fact about the mergers-and-acquisitions advisory business is that, =
if you run a company, and an investment banker comes in to pitch you on doi=
ng an acquisition:
=09That acquisition might or might not be a good idea for your company. In =
general the  track record of companies doing acquisitions is mixed to bad.=
=C2=A0=09It=E2=80=99s definitely a good idea for the banker! If you hire he=
r bank to do the acquisition, it will get a big fee and she=E2=80=99ll get =
a big bonus.
  [7]
=C2=A0If the deal turns out to be a dud for you, that=E2=80=99s not her pro=
blem.
  [8]



Everybody who has ever been pitched on doing a merger probably knows this. =
The banker sitting across from you is your trusted adviser, sure, but she=
=E2=80=99s also selling you something, and it=E2=80=99s your job to figure =
out if it=E2=80=99s a good idea for you. You know it=E2=80=99s a good idea =
for her.
We have   talked a lot in recent months about Goldman Sachs Group Inc. part=
ners who are disgruntled with the regime of Chief Executive Officer David S=
olomon, who runs Goldman like a normal public company rather than like the =
private partnership that it was for many years, and that it sort of pretend=
ed to be for another 20 years after that. (Usual disclosure: I used to work=
 at Goldman.)
Here is =E2=80=9CWhy former Goldman Sachs partners say they left the firm=
=E2=80=9D by Dakin Campbell at Insider, based on interviews with six anonym=
ous former partners. The basic complaints about Solomon boil down to (1) he=
 treats the partners like employees rather than like partners and (2) Goldm=
an put a lot of chips into a bet on consumer banking that didn=E2=80=99t wo=
rk out, and it is now doing an  embarrassing and costly retreat.
These complaints are related=C2=A0in the sense that they are both partly ab=
out nostalgia for the good old days, when Goldman was an elite player in hi=
gh finance that would never deign to do small-dollar consumer business, and=
 when the partners were the elite=C2=A0within the elite who were running th=
e show. Now =E2=80=9Cpartner=E2=80=9D is a courtesy title and Goldman is gi=
ving out toasters when you open a checking account, feh.
I often   quote John Whitehead=E2=80=99s  Investment Banking Services comma=
ndments around here. =E2=80=9CDon=E2=80=99t waste your time going after bus=
iness we don=E2=80=99t really want,=E2=80=9D is one of them. =E2=80=9CIt=E2=
=80=99s just as easy to get a first-rate piece of business as a second-rate=
 one,=E2=80=9D is another. My favorite is: =E2=80=9CImportant people like t=
o deal with other important people. Are you one?=E2=80=9D You can see why s=
ome Goldman partners who grew up with those commandments might be grumbling=
 now. They see Goldman going after business they don=E2=80=99t really want,=
 and they don=E2=80=99t feel as important as they used to.
Also though there=E2=80=99s this anecdote:

The bank is also now selling its GreenSky point-of-sale financing business.=
 Yet the acquisition, which Goldman made in 2021 for $2.2 billion, still ra=
nkles Goldmanites. The deal never made sense to many people inside Goldman,=
 especially those in its investment-banking division who had spent their ca=
reers advising corporate executives on takeover targets. =E2=80=A6
It's not just internal people who have noticed. One former partner who spok=
e with Insider said that in calling on clients, people had had to answer fo=
r Goldman's consumer-banking missteps.=C2=A0
"It's kind of embarrassing when you are showing up to a client pitching for=
 M&A business, position yourself as the best M&A advisor, pointing to these=
 credentials, and our own deals have been an absolute mess," the person sai=
d. "The number of jokes clients make, and there is some truth, why hire you=
 to do M&A if you can't even do your own M&A." =C2=A0

Oh come on! I do not believe for a second that some Goldman investment bank=
er showed up to pitch a merger and the client was like =E2=80=9Cnope, not t=
aking your merger pitch because Goldman bought GreenSky, proving that you=
=E2=80=99re dummies like everyone else.=E2=80=9D I mean, sure, as a joke. B=
ut the idea here is that previously Goldman would pitch M&A deals and the c=
