      Financial transactions tax
   =20
 =20

Chicago is a city with outsized global importance in the industry of high-s=
peed trading. If you are buying financial assets and selling them a millise=
cond later, you are disproportionately likely to be doing that from Chicago=
. Also there=E2=80=99s a decent chance that you make a nice living. Meanwhi=
le Chicago=E2=80=99s municipal budget does not look all that hot, and so it=
s civic leaders naturally think about how to raise more revenue. They see a=
ll these people doing all these high-speed trades and making a lot of money=
 doing it, and they think, well, if we charged these people just $1 per tra=
de we=E2=80=99d make up our budget shortfall in no time, and surely they wo=
uldn=E2=80=99t miss the dollar?
Bloomberg=E2=80=99s  Isis Almeida reports=C2=A0that they=E2=80=99ll miss th=
e dollar:

[Financial] firms=E2=80=99 commitment to the Windy City is being tested by =
some $800 million in taxes proposed by a new mayor staring down a budget ga=
p that=E2=80=99s swelled to half a billion dollars. One idea is a levy on f=
inancial transactions, which has alarmed companies already worried about a =
jump in crime that shows few signs of abating.
Behind the scenes, market makers and exchanges are working together to pres=
s their case with policymakers, with firms that typically compete with each=
 other sharing data to help explain their economic benefits to Chicago. Whi=
le executives haven=E2=80=99t explicitly threatened to leave, in private co=
nversations it=E2=80=99s clear they will consider quitting the city if crim=
e remains an issue and the financial transaction tax passes. =E2=80=A6
Mayor Brandon Johnson=E2=80=99s office said that no decision has been made =
on a transactions tax and the administration is open to dialogue with busin=
esses. Jason Lee, a senior adviser, noted that Chicago has a diversified ec=
onomy and =E2=80=9Cwe are lucky we don=E2=80=99t depend on a single industr=
y.=E2=80=9D
=E2=80=9CWe know the financial transaction one has been highly debated and =
there may be merit in that, but we look forward to that debate,=E2=80=9D he=
 said. =E2=80=9CWhat the mayor has said is that solutions cannot disproport=
ionately impact the working and middle class of our city.=E2=80=9D =E2=80=
=A6
Most importantly for the derivatives industry, Johnson has floated seeking =
another $100 million with a levy of $1 to $2 for every securities contract =
traded. That would boost costs by as much as 800%, according to CME. =E2=80=
=A6=C2=A0Illinois Governor=C2=A0JB Pritzker, who would need to approve a tr=
ansactions levy, opposes the idea, saying he=E2=80=99s worried =E2=80=9Cit =
would be easy for those companies and servers to move out of the state.=E2=
=80=9D

There are occasional proposals for=C2=A0a financial transactions tax at the=
 US federal level, and these discussions often point out that the UK has a =
somewhat similar tax. And people who oppose the tax are like =E2=80=9Cno th=
is would drive the financial industry to other countries without the tax,=
=E2=80=9D and people who support it are like =E2=80=9Cno, that=E2=80=99s du=
mb, London remains a global financial hub despite having a stamp tax, and t=
he advantages that the US has in terms of deep capital markets and the rule=
 of law are not going to be outweighed by a teeny tiny transaction tax.=E2=
=80=9D
But in Chicago? You could move to Florida, or even to like Evanston, and ge=
t the same capital markets but no transaction tax. A=C2=A0city=C2=A0is prob=
ably too small an entity to have its own capital markets regulation; it=E2=
=80=99s too easy to move to another city.=C2=A0It is the case that Chicago =
is unusually blessed, among global cities, with people who sit at computers=
 moving huge quantities of money around. But that does seem like kind of a =
fragile resource. They could put the computers anywhere.

