<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">But SpaceX is a private company,<a class=3D"fo=
otnote-index" href=3D"#footnote-4" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration=
: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; =
border-bottom-style: none !important; background-color: transparent !import=
ant; display: inline-block;">
<span>[4]</span>
</a>=C2=A0and Tesla is a public company. With a private company, the deal b=
etween the entrepreneur and the investors can kind of be whatever you want:=
 The company can have more or less whatever contractual terms or informal u=
nderstandings or governance structure the entrepreneur and the investors ag=
ree to. If Musk comes to the board of SpaceX and says =E2=80=9Chey you need=
 to lend me $1 billion for a week so I can win this fight I=E2=80=99m havin=
g online,=E2=80=9D the board can be like =E2=80=9Csure here you go you litt=
le rascal.=E2=80=9D It might not even have to tell shareholders. And if the=
 shareholders find out in the newspaper they can be like =E2=80=9Clol that=
=E2=80=99s our boy=E2=80=9D and everyone can be perfectly happy about it.=
=C2=A0</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Whereas with a public company, there are just =
rules that apply to all public companies, and that constrain the deals you =
can make. There are standard rules, enshrined in the US securities laws, re=
gulating what companies have to disclose to investors and how they have to =
communicate and what their relationship with their CEO can look like. And i=
f you break those rules it is mostly not a defense to say, like, =E2=80=9Cb=
ut my shareholders love me and think this is funny,=E2=80=9D or =E2=80=9Cbu=
t look how much money I am making for them.=E2=80=9D</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">If Elon Musk says nonsense about SpaceX online=
 and his investors are happy, then it=E2=80=99s fine.<a class=3D"footnote-i=
ndex" href=3D"#footnote-5" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !=
important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-b=
ottom-style: none !important; background-color: transparent !important; dis=
play: inline-block;">
<span>[5]</span>
</a>=C2=A0If Elon Musk says nonsense about Tesla online and his investors a=
re happy, but the US Securities and Exchange Commission is not happy, then =
<a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/32776778.258423/aH=
R0cHM6Ly93d3cuc2VjLmdvdi9uZXdzL3ByZXNzLXJlbGVhc2UvMjAxOC0yMjY/607f07ceef4b8=
524a319a23cB1dfb75f0" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=
=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; bord=
er-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: so=
lid; background-color: #ccc;"> the SEC can step in</a> and fine him $20 mil=
lion and make him stop being Tesla=E2=80=99s board chairman. Is that what T=
esla=E2=80=99s shareholders wanted? Probably not, no, but a public company =
is not just a deal between Musk and his shareholders; the SEC gets a say to=
o.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Similarly if Musk went to the board of SpaceX =
and said =E2=80=9CI would like you to spend a billion dollars of shareholde=
r money to build me a mansion that floats in midair 500 feet above Texas, p=
owered by several rocket thrusters,=E2=80=9D there would probably be permit=
ting issues, and maybe the directors would say no. But if the directors wer=
e cool with it and the shareholders were cool with it and the, uh, rocket h=
ouse regulators were cool with it then no securities regulator would get to=
 step in to say =E2=80=9Cno, this is not an acceptable use of shareholder m=
oney, you need to disclose this and put it to a vote.=E2=80=9D</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;"><a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness=
.com/click/32776778.258423/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cud3NqLmNvbS90ZWNoL2p1c3RpY2UtZGVw=
YXJ0bWVudC1wcm9iZS1zY3J1dGluaXplcy1lbG9uLW11c2stcGVya3MtYXQtdGVzbGEtZ29pbmc=
tYmFjay15ZWFycy0zNDkzZTMyMT9tb2Q9aXRwX3dzag/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBf34010=
c9" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=
=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: =
1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-c=
olor: #ccc;">Whereas</a>:</p>
<blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Federal prosecutors are scrutinizing personal =
benefits Tesla may have provided Elon Musk since 2017=E2=80=94longer than p=
reviously known=E2=80=94as part of a criminal investigation examining issue=
s including a proposed house for the chief executive.=C2=A0</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The U.S. Attorney=E2=80=99s Office for the Sou=
thern District of New York also has sought information about transactions b=
etween Tesla and other entities connected to the billionaire, people famili=
ar with the investigation said. Prosecutors have referenced the involvement=
 of a grand jury. =E2=80=A6</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Among the questions prosecutors are examining =
is whether Tesla properly disclosed perks Musk might have received. Interna=
l or external lawyers typically handle such disclosures. At Tesla, Musk has=
 at times personally guided what information to disclose to shareholders. I=
t couldn=E2=80=99t be learned whether that was the case with any perks that=
 prosecutors are scrutinizing. Tesla has said it generally doesn=E2=80=99t =
provide perks or other personal benefits to its top executives.</p>
</blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">A criminal investigation! At SpaceX, Musk coul=
d send the board a group text being like =E2=80=9Chey fyi I took $1 billion=
 out of the petty cash drawer for purposes, will put it back next week or s=
o=E2=80=9D and it=E2=80=99s fine.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Musk=E2=80=99s funniest Tesla perk is an <a hr=
ef=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/32776778.258423/aHR0cHM=
6Ly93d3cud3NqLmNvbS90ZWNoL2p1c3RpY2UtZGVwYXJ0bWVudC1wcm9iZS1zY3J1dGluaXplcy=
1lbG9uLW11c2stcGVya3MtYXQtdGVzbGEtZ29pbmctYmFjay15ZWFycy0zNDkzZTMyMT9tb2Q9a=
