b8524a319a23cC236dc1d8" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" targ=
et=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; bo=
rder-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: =
solid; background-color: #ccc;">  wrote a few weeks ago</a> about that Spac=
eX loan:</p>
<blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Back in 2018, when Musk was musing about takin=
g Tesla private, I argued that it made no sense: The public markets had bee=
n very kind to Tesla, allowing Musk to raise billions of dollars and giving=
 his company a huge valuation without actually imposing any real restrictio=
ns on him. ...</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">But I think I may have missed the main issue. =
The main issue is that Musk runs a web of companies, some of which need cas=
h and some of which have cash, and he is also in the business of starting o=
r buying other companies, creating more cash needs. If all of the companies=
 are private, he can sort of use their cash interchangeably: Sure, each com=
pany has different outside investors and its own board of directors, but th=
ey are all part of the Elon Musk family, and it=E2=80=99s not too hard to w=
ork something out. =E2=80=A6=C2=A0</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">But there are=C2=A0<em>some=C2=A0</em>limits f=
rom being public. =E2=80=A6=C2=A0If you want to run a web of companies that=
 all support each other, it might be easier if they are private.</p>
</blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">I don=E2=80=99t know, it=E2=80=99s just a stra=
nge situation.=C2=A0<em>In general=C2=A0</em>it makes sense for US public c=
ompanies to have rules like =E2=80=9Cthe CEO=E2=80=99s perks should be disc=
losed to shareholders=E2=80=9D or =E2=80=9Cthe CEO can=E2=80=99t go around =
lying about the company=E2=80=99s business=E2=80=9D or whatever. And the ro=
ugh rule that sophisticated shareholders of private companies can make info=
rmed choices to strike whatever deal they want with their CEOs, while publi=
c-company shareholders are protected by standard universal rules enforced b=
y the SEC and the Justice Department, also makes sense. In general, public-=
company=C2=A0CEOs should not be allowed to act like Elon Musk.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">But Elon Musk really has made a lot of money f=
or Tesla=E2=80=99s shareholders! And for SpaceX shareholders, but there see=
ms to be <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/32776778.=
258423/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuY25iYy5jb20vMjAyMy8wNy8xMy9lbG9uLW11c2stc3BhY2V4LW5l=
YXItMTUwLWJpbGxpb24tdmFsdWF0aW9uLmh0bWw/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB6959ca49" =
itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"c=
olor: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; =
border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color:=
 #ccc;"> no rush to go public</a> there. I increasingly think that, when he=
 was pretending to take Tesla private in 2018, Musk was in some sense serio=
us: He realized that, while going=C2=A0public was good for Tesla=E2=80=99s =
financing, it was a bad fit for his personality, and he kind of wanted to r=
everse=C2=A0it. CEOs often complain about the costs and constraints and sho=
rt-termism and legal risks of running a public company; regulators sometime=
s talk about bringing more companies into the public markets or about givin=
g more investors access to the private markets. But one important feature o=
f public markets, for better or worse, is that they are not very compatible=
 with=C2=A0the whole Elon Musk deal.=C2=A0</p>
