=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #0=
00000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-b=
ottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">=
 profile of Andy Golden</a>, the president of Princeton University=E2=80=99=
s endowment manager, which includes this lovely fact:</p>
<blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Today at PRINCO, Golden=C2=A0and his approxima=
tely 20-person team sit in one large room. They meet three times a week and=
 vote on investment decisions. The weighting of the votes, famous among tho=
se who know Golden well, is based on a secret formula he has in his head. T=
he mechanism for voting is =E2=80=9Codd and secret and unstable,=E2=80=9D h=
e says, declining to provide details.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The process and constant conversation between =
him and his team members keeps them engaged, he says. He believes this flow=
 of information can improve investment outcomes and attract and retain tale=
nt. And those things are necessities for his leadership method.</p>
</blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">I don=E2=80=99t know what that means but I cou=
ld imagine, like, programming a computer model that weights each analyst=E2=
=80=99s vote by (1) her track record of being correct in previous votes, (2=
) her expressed confidence in the current vote, (3) how much the CIO likes =
her personally and wants to get along with her, etc. And then you=C2=A0feed=
 the votes into that model and the computer is like =E2=80=9Cthis proposal =
passes with 9 Yes votes and 11 No votes, but the Yeses are a little better =
than the Noes.=E2=80=9D</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">In particular I could imagine Bridgewater Asso=
ciates <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/32776778.25=
8423/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMTYtMDItMD=
UvYnJpZGdld2F0ZXItcy1ib3NzZXMtYXJlLWZpZ2h0aW5nLW92ZXItc29tZXRoaW5nP2NtcGlkP=
UJCRDA5MjAyM19NT05FWVNUVUZGJnV0bV9tZWRpdW09ZW1haWwmdXRtX3NvdXJjZT1uZXdzbGV0=
dGVyJnV0bV90ZXJtPTIzMDkyMCZ1dG1fY2FtcGFpZ249bW9uZXlzdHVmZg/607f07ceef4b8524=
a319a23cB40f43ed5" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D=
"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-=
bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid=
; background-color: #ccc;">doing it on the computer</a>, using way more dat=
a to compute everyone=E2=80=99s vote weight, and publishing everyone=E2=80=
=99s coefficients. =E2=80=9CYour vote counted for 0.47 votes yesterday but =
then Dave found you a little annoying in a meeting and pushed the <a href=
=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/32776778.258423/aHR0cHM6L=
y93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS92aWV3L2FydGljbGVzLzIwMTktMDItMDEvYnJpZGdld2F0ZXIt=
YXNzb2NpYXRlcy1wcm92ZXMtc2VsZi1vYnNlc3Npb24tYWN0dWFsbHktd29ya3M_Y21waWQ9QkJ=
EMDkyMDIzX01PTkVZU1RVRkYmdXRtX21lZGl1bT1lbWFpbCZ1dG1fc291cmNlPW5ld3NsZXR0ZX=
ImdXRtX3Rlcm09MjMwOTIwJnV0bV9jYW1wYWlnbj1tb25leXN0dWZm/607f07ceef4b8524a319=
a23cB24ff1f2a" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_bl=
ank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bott=
om-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; ba=
ckground-color: #ccc;">negative feedback button</a> on the app, so now your=
 vote only counts for 0.44.=E2=80=9D</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Also though I could imagine=C2=A0<em>not=C2=A0=
</em>programming a computer model to do that, and just doing it informally =
in your head? Like Golden apparently does? What is life but interacting wit=
h people who give greater or lesser weight to your views and desires, and t=
rying to get your weight up? And having your own=C2=A0formula, in your own =
head, for how you weight other people=E2=80=99s views and desires?=C2=A0Eve=
ryone=E2=80=99s formula for that is odd and secret and unstable: Life chang=
es, friendships change, there=E2=80=99s no accounting for taste, the heart =
wants what it wants, etc. Except at Bridgewater the formula is probably in =
the computer.</p>
